        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="hc-endnote">One identity drives the page. Sell a fraction <em>x</em> of the stack at price <em>P</em> with tax <em>t</em>, and rebuy at <em>P_rebuy</em>: you end with <em>(1&minus;x) + x·(1&minus;t)·(P / P_rebuy)</em> of the stack you started with. The round-trip multiple on the sold slice is <em>(1&minus;t)·(P / P_rebuy)</em> &mdash; the number plotted above. Breakeven needs the rebuy more than <em>t</em> below the sale, which is why the tax rate moves the crossing. Your stack size cancels out of all of it, which is why the BTC input changes nothing but the dollar labels. Tax assumes a fully appreciated stack (zero cost basis): a real basis softens the haircut.</p>
      <p class="hc-endnote">Two limits worth naming. When no dip arrives inside two years the rebuy happens anyway, at the two-year price &mdash; often <em>higher</em> than the sale, which is how a round trip loses coins rather than merely failing to gain them; those rows are in the table marked "no dip". And at the extremes of the channel the record thins out: the neighborhood widens automatically to keep a workable sample, so a figure at the far upper band rests on fewer entries than one near trend. The entry count and band width are stated with every verdict.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

